{{Redirect|Noto Kiriko Matsuri|asteroid|Kiriko Matsuri (asteroid)}} {{Referencing style|date=December 2022}} [[File:Noto Yosakoi Wakura 01.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|ja|石崎奉燈祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|qq=}} held in {{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao|qq=}}.]]
'''Noto Kiriko Matsuri''' (能登キリコ祭り) are festivals held across the {{ill|Noto Peninsula|ja|能登半島|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Peninsula|qq=}} in {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa Prefecture|qq=}}.<ref name="bluesignal">{{Cite journal|title=Travel West to Japan Heritage: Noto's Festivals that Invite the Gods|journal=Blue Signal|publisher={{ill|JR West|ja|西日本旅客鉄道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR West|qq=}}|date=July 2019|issue=July 2019|url=https://www.westjr.co.jp/company/info/issue/bsignal/19_vol_185/issue/01.html|accessdate=2022-12-30}}</ref><ref name="sankeiphoto">{{Cite web|title=The Sublime Beauty of Japan: Lantern Festivals on the Noto Peninsula|website=Sankei Photo|date=October 2, 2019|url=https://www.sankei.com/photo/story/news/191006/sty1910060001-n1.html|accessdate=2022-12-30}}</ref><ref name="asa20220529">{{Cite news|title=Noto's Iconic Kiriko Festivals: Taō Tsuchiya and the Self-Defense Forces Join In|newspaper=Asahi Shimbun Digital|date=May 29, 2022|url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASQ5X747GQ5QPISC001.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20220529163550/https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASQ5X747GQ5QPISC001.html|archivedate=May 29, 2022|accessdate=2022-12-30}}</ref>.
== Overview == The festivals are characterized by the use of tall, rectangular lantern floats called {{ill|Kiriko|ja|切籠|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiriko|qq=}} or {{ill|Hōtō|ja|奉燈|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōtō|qq=}}.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=134}} While some kiriko lanterns exceed 10 meters in height, most are between 4 to 6 meters and are carried by groups of around 20 people.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=135}} In some areas, they are also referred to as "Oakashii" (御明かし). The festivals typically feature processions through town streets to a temporary shrine (often located near water or in open spaces) before returning to the main shrine.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=134}} Some festivals include sea crossings during their processions.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=134}}
Held primarily from July to September as summer or autumn festivals, they occur at about 200 locations throughout the peninsula.<ref name="bluesignal"/><ref name="sankeiphoto"/><ref name="asa20220529"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=134}} Many of these festivals originated with prayers for the prevention of epidemics<ref name="bluesignal"/> or for bountiful harvests and fishing.<ref name="sankeiphoto"/>
== History == The origins of the Kiriko Matsuri are partly rooted in oral traditions, with limited documentation. One of the earliest references to kiriko can be found in the 1647 (Shōhō 3) festival records of {{ill|Wajima Sumiyoshi Shrine|ja|輪島住吉神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wajima Sumiyoshi Shrine|qq=}}.<ref name="bluesignal"/><ref name="asa20220529"/> The {{ill|Abare Matsuri|ja|あばれ祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abare Matsuri|qq=}} of {{ill|Ushitsu|ja|宇出津|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ushitsu|qq=}}, held at {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社 (能登町)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasaka Shrine|qq=}}, is said to have started during the Kanbun era (1661–1673), although this is debated.<ref name="asa20220529"/> The festivals are generally believed to have originated during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}} and derive either from the {{ill|Gion Matsuri|ja|祇園祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Matsuri|qq=}} in Kyoto or from midsummer Shinto rites.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=134}}
In December 1997 (Heisei 9), the "Noto Kiriko Matsuri" was designated as a {{ill|Folk Cultural Property Requiring Measures for Documentation|ja|記録作成等の措置を講ずべき無形の民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Folk Cultural Property Requiring Measures for Documentation|qq=}} by the national government.<ref>{{Cultural Heritage Online|161401|Noto's Kiriko Festivals}}</ref> In 2015, the festivals were recognized as part of the Japan Heritage program under the title "Islands of Light: Noto Peninsula's Passionate Kiriko Festivals."<ref name="asa20220529"/><ref>[http://www.bunka.go.jp/seisaku/bunkazai/nihon_isan/ichiran.html List of Japan Heritage Sites] - Agency for Cultural Affairs</ref>
== Kiriko == [[File:Wajima Kiriko Art Museum ac (13).jpg|thumb|Kiriko lanterns on display at the Wajima Kiriko Art Museum]] [[File:Wajima Kiriko Art Museum ac (6).jpg|thumb|Kiriko lantern with auspicious characters]]
Kiriko lanterns are typically tall, rectangular {{ill|Andon|ja|行灯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Andon|qq=}} with "auspicious characters" (吉祥文字) representing prayers and wishes inscribed on the front.<ref name="bluesignal"/> The back often features elaborate paintings, such as warrior imagery or landscapes.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=135}} The lanterns are topped with a {{ill|Kirizuma roof|ja|切妻屋根|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kirizuma roof|qq=}} and adorned with decorations like paper streamers and {{ill|Chōchin|ja|提灯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōchin|qq=}}.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=135}} Designs and dimensions vary by region, with some kiriko resembling the curved shapes of {{ill|Nebuta|ja|青森ねぶた|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nebuta|qq=}} floats.
It is believed that kiriko originated as small, hand-held bamboo sticks with paper lanterns ("Sasa Kiriko") and gradually grew larger, reaching their current size by the late Edo period.<ref name="bluesignal"/><ref name="asa20220529"/> However, depopulation has led to a shortage of carriers in some regions, prompting adjustments like rescheduling festivals to weekends.<ref name="sankeiphoto"/>
== Major Kiriko Festivals == Dates vary annually. Listed below are notable examples:
; Nanao * {{ill|Mutomachi Festival|ja|互市祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mutomachi Festival|qq=}} - Early July * {{ill|Nanao Gion Matsuri|ja|七尾祇園祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao Gion Matsuri|qq=}} - Early July * {{ill|Mukōda Fire Festival|lt=Mukōda Fire Festival|lt=Mukōda no Hi Matsuri|ja|向田の火祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mukōda no Hi Matsuri|qq=}} - Last Saturday of July * {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|ja|石崎奉燈祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|qq=}} - First Saturday of August<ref name="asa20220529"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=136}}
; Wajima * Wajima Taisai - August 22–25<ref name="asa20220529"/><ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=137}}
; Suzu * {{ill|Iida Tōrōyama Matsuri|ja|飯田町燈籠山祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iida Tōrōyama Matsuri|qq=}} - Late July * {{ill|Hōraku Matsuri|ja|宝立七夕キリコ祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōraku Matsuri|qq=}} - First Saturday of August<ref name="sankeiphoto"/>
== Kiriko Festival Facilities == === Wajima Kiriko Art Museum === {{Main|Wajima Kiriko Art Museum}} The museum in {{ill|Wajima|ja|輪島市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wajima|qq=}} showcases 31 kiriko lanterns and explains the festivals.<ref name="asa20220529"/> Opened in 2015, it serves as a cultural hub for the events.<ref>[https://wajima-kiriko.com/ Wajima Kiriko Art Museum]</ref>
