Kiriko lanterns are typically tall, rectangular {{ill|Andon|ja|行灯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Andon|qq=}} with "auspicious characters" (吉祥文字) representing prayers and wishes inscribed on the front.<ref name="bluesignal"/> The back often features elaborate paintings, such as warrior imagery or landscapes.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=135}} The lanterns are topped with a [[:en:Gable roof|Kirizuma roof]] and adorned with decorations like paper streamers and {{ill|Chōchin|ja|提灯|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōchin|qq=}}.<ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=135}} Designs and dimensions vary by region, with some kiriko resembling the curved shapes of [[:en:Aomori Nebuta Matsuri|Nebuta]] floats.
It is believed that kiriko originated as small, hand-held bamboo sticks with paper lanterns ("Sasa Kiriko") and gradually grew larger, reaching their current size by the late Edo period.<ref name="bluesignal"/><ref name="asa20220529"/> However, depopulation has led to a shortage of carriers in some regions, prompting adjustments like rescheduling festivals to weekends.<ref name="sankeiphoto"/>
== Major Kiriko Festivals == Dates vary annually. Listed below are notable examples:
; Nanao * {{ill|Mutomachi Festival|ja|互市祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mutomachi Festival|qq=}} - Early July * {{ill|Nanao Gion Matsuri|ja|七尾祇園祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao Gion Matsuri|qq=}} - Early July * {{ill|Mukōda Fire Festival|lt=Mukōda Fire Festival|lt=Mukōda no Hi Matsuri|ja|向田の火祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mukōda no Hi Matsuri|qq=}} - Last Saturday of July * {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|ja|石崎奉燈祭|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishizaki Hōtō Matsuri|qq=}} - First Saturday of August<ref name="asa20220529"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=136}}
; Wajima * Wajima Taisai - August 22–25<ref name="asa20220529"/><ref name="bluesignal"/>{{sfn|JTB|2018|p=137}}
; Suzu * {{ill|Iida Tōrōyama Matsuri|ja|飯田町燈籠山祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iida Tōrōyama Matsuri|qq=}} - Late July * {{ill|Hōraku Matsuri|ja|宝立七夕キリコ祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōraku Matsuri|qq=}} - First Saturday of August<ref name="sankeiphoto"/>
== Kiriko Festival Facilities == === Wajima Kiriko Art Museum === {{Main|Wajima Kiriko Art Museum}} The museum in [[:en:Wajima, Ishikawa|Wajima]] showcases 31 kiriko lanterns and explains the festivals.<ref name="asa20220529"/> Opened in 2015, it serves as a cultural hub for the events.<ref>[https://wajima-kiriko.com/ Wajima Kiriko Art Museum]</ref>
